The 24-item openness to experience subscale of the 120-item IPIP-NEO (Johnson, 2014) also assesses 6 facets of openness to experience: imagination, artistic interests, emotionality, adventurousness, intellect, and liberalism.  We will also compute correlations between each facet and indices of passion quantity.  This analysis will be done for exploratory purposes to determine if there are certain facets most responsible for a positive correlation between openness and passion quantity.

Complete design of the online survey is as follows:

The first page of the survey will present participants with an INFORMED CONSENT page that contains all the standard consent form details (purpose of research, data management procedures, risks/benefits, etc.).  Participants will only be able to access the remaining pages of the survey if they select "I agree" at the end of this page.

The remaining pages of the online survey will ask participants to:

(a) respond to 2 items from the openness subscale of the Ten Item Personality Inventory (Gosling et al., 2003);

(b) respond to the 24-item openness to experience subscale of the 120-item IPIP-NEO (Johnson, 2014).  The initial ordering of the items will be randomized;

(c) list their four favourite activities;

(d) answer items from the passion criteria subscale of the Passion Scale (Vallerand et al., 2003) to assess the passion criteria for each activity.  Participants will answer passion criteria items for each activity, starting with their favourite activity and ending with their fourth-favourite activity;

 (e) answer demographic questions (e.g., age, ethnicity), report their Prolific ID numbers, and answer an honesty check item.

The final page of the survey will thank participants for participating in the study and provide additional details as part of the debriefing procedures.

